ystem sees it as satisfying **every** optional interface — even ones the external binary didn't declare support for.\\n\\nThis matters because the rest of the codebase uses type assertions to check capabilities:\\n\\n```go\\nif hs, ok := a.(agent.HookSupport); ok {\\n    // only called if agent supports hooks\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIf `*Agent` were returned directly, these checks would **always** succeed, regardless of what the binary actually supports.\\n\\n**The solution:** `Wrap` creates a thin wrapper struct that only forwards the interfaces matching the declared capabilities. For example:\\n\\n- Binary declares only `hooks` → returns `*hooksAgent` (satisfies `agent.Agent` + `HookSupport` only)\\n- Binary declares nothing → returns `*baseAgent` (satisfies only `agent.Agent`)\\n- Binary declares everything → returns `*fullAgent` (satisfies all interfaces)\\n\\n**Why not embedding?** The comment on line 17-18 explains: Go embedding would expose all methods from `*Agent`, defeating the purpose. Each wrapper must explicitly list only the methods it should expose.\\n\\nThe trade-off is boilerplate (each wrapper re-declares its forwarding methods), but it gives correct runtime interface satisfaction that matches what the external binary actually supports.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":12461,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":19329,\"output_tokens\":414,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":12461,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYiG9HLiV1aGTUwfqHoh2\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"a23a0255-98b3-4d5e-a469-92b4834c2588\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T15:17:22.727Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"a23a0255-98b3-4d5e-a469-92b4834c2588\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/nodo/work